# React Component Props Pattern

When creating React components, always follow this pattern:

1. Define props type interface
2. Pass typed props object to component
3. Destructure props inside component body

## Pattern

```typescript
// ✅ GOOD - Type props, then destructure inside
type ComponentNameProps = {
  prop1: string;
  prop2: number;
  onAction: () => void;
};

export function ComponentName(props: ComponentNameProps) {
  const { prop1, prop2, onAction } = props;
  
  return (
    <View>
      <Text>{prop1}</Text>
    </View>
  );
}
```

```typescript
// ❌ BAD - Destructuring in function signature
export function ComponentName({ prop1, prop2, onAction }: ComponentNameProps) {
  return (
    <View>
      <Text>{prop1}</Text>
    </View>
  );
}
```

## Benefits

- Cleaner function signature
- Easier to see all props at a glance
- Better for refactoring
- Consistent code style across the project
